        optionFeedback: [`Degranulation is triggered by calcium influx and cytoskeletal activation in response to stimuli that activate neutrophils.`,`Prostaglandins are produced by phospholipase A2-mediated digestion of membrane phospholipids to generate arachidonic acid, which is then converted to prostaglandins by the action of cyclooxygenase. `,`Upon activation, neutrophils produce reactive oxygen species such as superoxide in granules, which are converted to the more potent microbicidal halides by the action of the granule enzyme myeloperoxidase. These halides (and other free radicals) destroy phagocytosed microbes.  `,`Oxygen consumption is increased in activated neutrophils, not decreased. `,`Hydrogen peroxide is also derived from the reactive oxygen species superoxide, but this process does not require myeloperoxidase.`],
