        optionFeedback: [`Integrins are involved in leukocyte migration into tissues, so their deficiency would result in reduced numbers of neutrophils in the abscess.`,`Microtubular defects interfere with degranulation, but the normal neutrophil function in the presence of normal serum rules out a cell-intrinsic defect.`,`The fact that neutrophils are elevated in the blood and present in the tissues rules out a migration defect, as does the normal chemotaxis assay. The neutrophils can destroy bacteria in the presence of normal serum but not in the patient’s serum, suggesting that there is a deficiency of some circulating factor involved in microbial killing. The major candidates are antibodies and complement proteins, and complement levels are normal, pointing to antibodies as the problem. In this case, in the absence of antibodies, the microbes are not adequately opsonized, and therefore not properly phagocytosed and destroyed intracellularly.`,`If neutrophils had a defect in the generation of oxygen-derived free radicals, they would not be able to kill organisms even in the presence of normal serum.`,`Selectins are involved in leukocyte migration into tissues, so their deficiency would result in reduced numbers of neutrophils in the abscess.`],
