        q: `A 72-year-old man with severe emphysema has had worsening right ventricular failure for the past 5 years. For the past 4 days, he has had fever and increasing dyspnea. A chest radiograph shows patchy areas of consolidation and an accumulation of fluid in the pleural spaces. Fluid obtained by thoracentesis appears yellowish-green, has a specific gravity of 1.030 (normal &#126;1.00), and contains degenerating neutrophils.  Which of the following is the most likely cause of this fluid accumulation?`,
        q2: ``,
        q3: [],
        option: [`Decreased intravascular colloid osmotic pressure`, `Increased intravascular hydrostatic pressure`,`Lymphatic obstruction`,`Increased renal sodium retention`,`Increased vascular permeability`],
        optionFeedback: [`Colloid osmotic pressure falls mainly because of decreased production of albumin (as in liver disease) or increased loss of albumin (as in kidney disease). Decreased colloid osmotic pressure leads to transudation of fluid and edema in multiple tissues.`,`Hydrostatic pressure of the blood increases in conditions of compromised venous return, as in congestive heart failure. The increased pressure also leads to transudation of plasma and edema formation. This could have happened in this patient if he had congestive heart failure not complicated by pneumonia.`,`Blocked lymphatic drainage, as may occur with metastasis of cancers to lymph nodes, may lead to lymphedema, usually comprised of a protein-poor, transudate-like fluid.`,`Reduced renal perfusion activates the renin-angiotensin system, leading to sodium retention and increased blood pressure and blood volume. This does not cause edema, by itself, but it often occurs as a maladaptive response in the setting of left-sided heart failure, in which fluid “overload” due to sodium retention may exacerbate pulmonary edema and pulmonary effusions. The effusions that are seen are transudates, however, unlike what is seen here.`,`The clinical history of fever and worsening pulmonary function and the X-ray are indicative of acute pneumonia. The pleural fluid has a high specific gravity, indicating leakage of plasma proteins, and contains neutrophils. These are typical of exudates, which result from increased vascular permeability (as in acute inflammation).`],
