        option: [`Basophil`, `B lymphocyte`,` CD4+ lymphocyte`,`Monocyte`,`CD8+ lymphocyte`],
        optionFeedback: [`Basophils are the circulating counterparts of tissue mast cells. They may be involved in allergic reactions, but they do not respond to IFN-γ and are not microbicidal.`,`B lymphocytes are stimulated by IFN-γ (together with antigen and other signals) to produce some IgG types (more so in mice than in humans), but these cells are not microbicidal.`,`CD4+ T cells respond to IFN-γ by differentiating into Th1 cells, which can produce IFN-γ and activate the microbicidal function of monocytes and macrophages, but CD4+ T cells are not themselves microbicidal.`,`IFN-γ is the most potent cytokine known for activating blood monocytes and tissue macrophages. This pathway of activation (called the classical pathway) induces strong microbicidal activity in the cells. `,`CD8+ cells are not microbicidal, although they can kill cells harboring microbes in the cytosol.`],
