        optionFeedback: [`C1q binds to antibodies (and mannose-binding lectin) and initiates the classical (and lectin) pathways of complement activation.`,`Histamine is a vasoactive amine produced by mast cells and other cells and induces vasodilation and smooth muscle contraction.`,`Leukotrienes are synthesized by the action of lipoxygenase, which is not inhibited by nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs. It is inhibited, however, by steroids.`,`Nitric oxide (NO) is synthesized by the action of nitric oxide synthase, which is also not inhibited by nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs.`,`Aspirin, the oldest nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug, works by inhibiting the enzyme cyclooxygenase and thus the synthesis of prostaglandins (and thromboxanes). Remarkably, aspirin has been used to treat inflammation since about 1900, but its mechanism of action was defined only in the 1970s. None of the other substances is inhibited by aspirin.`],
