        optionFeedback: [`Fibroblast proliferation is seen during repair by scarring and is not a component of acute inflammation.`,`Caseous necrosis is a special type of necrosis in which the tissue in the center of granulomas dies, developing an amorphous “cheese-like,” crumbling consistency.`,`The clinical history and laboratory findings indicate acute abdominal inflammation likely secondary to a bacterial infection. Laparotomy reveals acute salpingitis. The fallopian tube is distended by the accumulation of pus, a collection of dead neutrophils, bacteria, and tissue, formed as a result of liquefactive necrosis.`,`Eosinophilic inflammation is typical of helminthic infections and allergic reactions.`,`Squamous metaplasia is the conversion of one type of epithelium (usually columnar) to tougher squamous epithelium as a reaction to chronic exposure to irritants.`],
